                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well tricky one, but if you look of the basis that the 3 chars should be self sufficient and be able to do different types of zone (i.e. both outdoors and dungeon) there is some key features that are nice to have.
<br />

<br />
Healer: Options are Shaman, Druid, Cleric. Since you want to have a chanter in the trio I say shaman is opted out since the chanter have slow and speed wich are key element. So its either a druid or a cleric. Druid is more versatile with track and spells but is a weaker HP buffer and a weaker healer.
<br />

<br />
Tank: For you to be able to do different zones a tank is almost a must, to obvious choices are warrior, paladin and shadowknight. Other classes can tank if they are well equipped but starting fresh these 3 are best imo. Warrior ofcourse can tank the meanest mobs but in a trio it dont bring much else to the table so go for Sk or a Pally. Big bonus is the knights ability to grab initial aggro wich allows the chanter to get slow in asap.
<br />

<br />
I would either go for:
<br />
1) Chanter, Druid, Pally
<br />
2) Chanter, Cleric, Shadowknight
<br />

<br />
If you are a good charmer option 1 is better due to the druids snare, a well played Pally with his stuns is a good friend to the chanter also. I 3 box setup 2 on occasion but perhaps option 1 is a better setup.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />----------------------------------------------------------------------
<br />
<span style="font-style: italic"><span style="font-weight: bold">Ardbeg Whiskeylover</span></span>
<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Lvl 66 Enchanter
<br />
Wind of Tranquility
<br />
Antonious Bayle server</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
